why these inequalities persist in the twenty-first century, pointing to discriminatory hiring and supervisory practices that ultimately grant educated whites access to the most desirable positions. Additionally, he shows us how workers navigate these inequalities under the same roof, making sense of their jobs, their identities, and each other in a world that reinforces their separateness. Front of the House, Back of the House takes us behind the scenes of the food service industry, providing a window into the unequal lives of white and Latino restaurant workers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aDiscrimination in employmentzUnited States. 0aHispanic AmericansxEmployment. 0aRacismzUnited States. 0aRestaurant managementzUnited States. 0aRestaurantszUnited StatesxEmployees. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aBrown-Collar Labor.  aEconomic Mobility.  aLabor Inequalities.  aLabor Inequality.  aLabor Politics.  aManagement Structures.  aRestaurant Inequality.  aService Industry.  aService Inequality.  aSocial Inequality.  aSociology of Labor.  aSociology of Work.  aWorker Mobility.  aWorkplace Inequality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z97831107227030 cprintz978147980061240uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479800612.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97